Interface Tree<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - component type of this Tree
    All Superinterfaces:
    FilterMonadic<Kind.IterableKind<?>,T>, Iterable<T>, Kind<Kind.IterableKind<?>,T>, TraversableOnce<T>

    public interface Tree<T>
extends TraversableOnce<T>, FilterMonadic<Kind.IterableKind<?>,T>

    A general Tree interface.

      • isLeaf

        boolean isLeaf()
        Checks if this Tree is a leaf. A tree is a leaf if it is a Node with no children. Because the empty tree is no Node, it is not a leaf by definition.
        Returns:
        true if this tree is a leaf, false otherwise.

      • isBranch

        default boolean isBranch()
        Checks if this Tree is a branch. A Tree is a branch if it is a Node which has children. Because the empty tree is not a Node, it is not a branch by definition.
        Returns:
        true if this tree is a branch, false otherwise.

      • filterOption

        Tree<Some<T>> filterOption(Predicate<? super T> predicate)
        Description copied from interface: FilterMonadic
        Returns a new FilterMonadic consisting of Some elements if there are elements which satisfy the given predicate. Otherwise the results contains one None element. Please note, that the result will not contain a mixture of Some and None elements.

        This method is intended to be used with monadic types which may have only one value, e.g. Lazy and Match (resp. MatchMonad).

        Specified by:
        filterOption in interface FilterMonadic<Kind.IterableKind<?>,T>
        Parameters:
        predicate - A predicate
        Returns:
        a new FilterMonadic instance

      • flatMapM

        <U> Tree<U> flatMapM(Function<? super T,? extends Kind<? extends Kind.IterableKind<?>,? extends U>> mapper)
        Description copied from interface: FilterMonadic
        Flat maps the elements of this elements of a new type preserving their order, if any.

        This method effectively does call 

        this.flatMap((Function<? super T, ? extends M<? extends U>>) mapper);
        It exists, because Java's type system (the lack of higher-order kinds) does not allow us to define an interface containing the mentioned flatMap method.
        Specified by:
        flatMapM in interface FilterMonadic<Kind.IterableKind<?>,T>
        Type Parameters:
        U - Component type of the flat mapped FilterMonadic
        Parameters:
        mapper - A mapper.
        Returns:
        a flat mapped FilterMonadic

      • flatten

        Tree<Object> flatten()
        Description copied from interface: FilterMonadic
        Flattens a FilterMonadic.

        The semantics may vary from class to class. The commonality is, that some kind of wrapped state is recursively unwrapped.

        Example: 

        ((1, 2), 3, (4, (5, 6))).flatten() = (1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6)
        Specified by:
        flatten in interface FilterMonadic<Kind.IterableKind<?>,T>
        Returns:
        A flattened version of this FilterMonadic.
